M|Over|Good|most "strategies" are just goals, visions, or wish lists—not actual strategies. Real st consists of a coherent kernel w/ three parts: diagnosis (what's really going on), guiding policy (overall approach), and coherent actions (coordinated steps).
M|Over|Rume|bad st is shockingly common, even in successful companies. It stems from inability or unwillingness to make hard choices, confusion btw goals and st, and template-thinking that produces generic "strategies" empty of cn.
M|Over|tx|The Kernel framework provides a diagnostic tool for evaluating whether you have a real st or just st-sounding words. Good st acknowledges obstacles, makes hard choices abt what not to do, and coordinates actions to concentrate power at decisive points. Bad st mistakes goals for st, ignores challenges, and fails to translate vision into actionable steps.
M|Over|**Ke|The most common cause of bad st is a weak diagnosis. The second is confusing goals w/ st. Goals, ambitions, visions, missions, values—none of these are st. st is fundamentally abt what you'll do in rp to a challenge.
M|Idea|- **|Annual or multi-year st dv
M|Idea|- **|Reacting to mk changes or competitive threats
M|Idea|- **|Deciding where to invest limited resources
M|Idea|- **|Determining which markets to enter and how to compete
M|Idea|- **|Getting teams coordinated on priorities
M|Idea|- **|Auditing existing st to identify weaknesses
M|Idea|- **|Rapidly formulating rp to sudden challenges
M|Warn|it|Your "st" is mostly goals and aspirations w/o addressing how to achieve them
M|Warn|it|st documents are filled w/ buzzwords, generic statements, and consultant-speak
M|Warn|it|Different teams interpret the st completely differently
M|Warn|it|No one can articulate what trade-offs the st requires
M|Warn|it|The st doesn't acknowledge sig obstacles or challenges
M|Warn|it|Leadership confuses "being st" w/ long-term thinking or ambition
M|Warn|it|st sn produce lists of things to do w/o clear prioritization
M|1. D|**Pu|A great deal of st work is trying to figure out what is going on—not just deciding what to do, but comprehending the situation and identifying the biggest barriers to forward progress.
M|1. D|**Wh|Simplifying the overwhelming complexity of reality to identify ct aspects of the situation. A good diagnosis names or classifies the challenge and provides a frame for further action.
M|1. D|**Wh|A laundry list of every problem or challenge. Diagnosis requires judgment abt what matters most.
M|1. D|**Qu|
M|1. D|it|What is the fundamental nature of the challenge we face?
M|1. D|it|What are the ct bottlenecks or leverage points?
M|1. D|it|Which obstacles, if removed, wld most advance our position?
M|1. D|it|What patterns explain our current situation?
M|1. D|it|What assumptions are we making that might be wrong?
M|1. D|**Ou|A clear, simple statement of the core challenge that everyone can understand and that reveals where to focus effort.
M|1. D|**Ex|Netflix (2007): "Our DVD rental business is highly profitable but will eventually be disrupted by streaming vd delivery. The ct challenge is building streaming capabilities before someone else dominates that space."
M|2. F|**Pu|Outline an overall approach to overcoming the obstacles highlighted in the diagnosis. Like guardrails on a highway, guiding policy directs and constrains action w/o fully defining it.
M|2. F|**Wh|A general method or approach for dealing w/ the challenge. It channels action in certain directions w/o specifying exactly what shall be done.
M|2. F|**Wh|A goal, vision, or desired outcome. "Be the mk leader" is not a guiding policy—it's a goal.
M|2. F|**Ch|
M|2. F|it|Anticipates and reduces the complexity of the challenge
M|2. F|it|Exploits leverage or sources of advantage
M|2. F|it|Makes hard choices abt what not to do
M|2. F|it|Creates actionable boundaries for decisions
M|2. F|**Qu|
M|2. F|it|What general approach will we take to address this challenge?
M|2. F|it|What are we ruling out or saying no to?
M|2. F|it|What advantage can we cr or exploit?
M|2. F|it|What's our theory for how this approach overcomes the obstacle?
M|2. F|**Ou|A clear statement of approach that rules out many possible actions while enabling coherent ones.
M|2. F|**Ex|Netflix guiding policy: "Shift investment aggressively toward streaming technology and cn licensing while maintaining DVD business for cash flow. Accept lower margins during transition."
M|3. D|**Pu|Specify the set of feasible actions that are coordinated w/ one another to accomplish the guiding policy. These are steps that work together, each building on the others.
M|3. D|**Wh|Concrete, coordinated steps designed to carry out the guiding policy. The actions shd be coherent—they shd reinforce each other rather than scatter effort.
M|3. D|**Wh|A random list of initiatives or projects. Coherent actions bd on each other systematically.
M|3. D|**Ch|
M|3. D|it|Specific enough to be implemented
M|3. D|it|Coordinated—one action supports another
M|3. D|it|Resource-feasible given constraints
M|3. D|it|Directly address the diagnosis through the guiding policy
M|3. D|**Qu|
M|3. D|it|What specific actions will we take in the nx planning period?
M|3. D|it|How do these actions reinforce each other?
M|3. D|it|What resources (people, money, time) does each require?
M|3. D|it|What's the logical sequencing and dependencies?
M|3. D|it|What will we stop doing to resource these actions?
M|3. D|**Ou|A coordinated set of 3-7 specific actions w/ clear owners, timelines, and resource commitments.
M|3. D|**Ex|Netflix coherent actions (2007):
M|3. D|tx|1. License streaming rights from major studios
M|3. D|tx|2. bd streaming technology platform
M|3. D|tx|3. ig streaming into existing subscriber base (free w/ DVD subscription initially)
M|3. D|tx|4. Develop recommendation algorithms for streaming catalog
M|3. D|tx|5. Gradually shift mk emphasis from DVD to streaming
M|4. T|**Ba|
M|4. T|- **|Gibberish masquerading as st concepts or arguments
M|4. T|- **|Not defining the core challenge or ignoring it
M|4. T|- **|Confusing desired outcomes w/ a method to achieve them
M|4. T|- **|Objectives that fail to address ct issues or are impractical given available resources
M|4. T|**Go|
M|4. T|it|Creates new sources of advantage or exploits existing ones
M|4. T|it|Makes hard choices and trade-offs explicit
M|4. T|it|Concentrates resources at decisive points
M|4. T|it|Provides clear link from diagnosis → policy → actions
M|4. T|it|Can be explained simply to someone outside the organization
M|4. T|**Ap|rv your kernel. Does each cp exist? Does it pass the qual tests? If not, iterate.
M|Cont|tx|General Schwarzkopf faced the challenge of removing Iraqi forces from Kuwait. Iraq had the world's fourth-largest army, entrenched in defensive positions, w/ exp from the Iran-Iraq war.
M|Appl|**Di|Iraqi strength was in static defense and numbers. Their weakness was in mobile operations, command-and-control, and air defense. The ct leverage point: if coalition forces cld achieve air supremacy and attack from an unexpected direction, Iraqi static defenses became irrelevant.
M|Appl|**Gu|Achieve complete air dominance first, then execute rapid flanking attack from the west (through desert Iraq considered impassable) while feinting frontal assault to fix Iraqi forces in place.
M|Appl|**Co|
M|Appl|tx|1. Six-week air cg to destroy Iraqi air force, command infrastructure, and supply lines
M|Appl|tx|2. bd up forces in Saudi Arabia while conducting visible amphibious assault training (deception)
M|Appl|tx|3. Secretly move heavy armor divisions far west into desert
M|Appl|tx|4. Launch ground war w/ massive western flanking movement ("left hook")
M|Appl|tx|5. Fix Iraqi forces w/ Marine feint toward Kuwait City from south
M|Appl|tx|6. Cut off retreat rt w/ airborne and armored units
M|Outc|tx|100-hour ground war, decisive victory w/ minimal coalition casualties. sc came from coherent st where diagnosis identified leverage points, guiding policy exploited them, and actions coordinated to maximum effect.
M|What|- **|Identified Iraqi weakness (mobility, C&C) vs. strength (static defense)
M|What|- **|Avoided attacking Iraqi strengths, exploited specific weaknesses
M|What|- **|Each action reinforced others; deception enabled flanking; air cg enabled ground speed
M|What|- **|Said "no" to direct frontal assault despite political pressure for quick action
M|Anti|**St|Using consulting frameworks to gn generic strategies ("We will be the mk leader in X by leveraging Y to deliver Z to cs"). These produce fluff, not st.
M|Anti|**Co|"Our st is to grow 20% per year" or "Our st is to be #1 in cs satisfaction"—these are goals, not st.
M|Anti|**La|Calling a collection of projects a "st" w/o coherence or clear diagnosis.
M|Anti|**Ig|Strategies that don't acknowledge or address sig challenges facing the organization.
M|Anti|**Do|Too many priorities, which means no actual priorities—resources scatter ineffectively.
M|Anti|**Bl|Goals that sound inspiring but are disconnected from current reality or resources (Rumelt calls this "bad st objectives").
M|Anti|**An|Doing extensive al but failing to diagnose what actually matters—every problem weighted equally.
M|Anti|**Ha|Refusing to acknowledge hard truths abt competitive position or mk realities.
M|Rela|- **|st inflection points often trigger need for new diagnosis and st
M|Rela|- **|Complementary framework w/ five st choices—can be combined w/ Kernel
M|Rela|- **|Managing through the difficult execution of hard st choices
M|Rela|- **|Creating uncontested mk space—one tp of guiding policy
M|Rela|- **|Observe-Orient-Decide-Act—the "orient" phase is diagnosis
M|Rela|- **|Identifying sources of enduring competitive advantage (feeds into guiding policy)
M|Rela|- **|Strip assumptions to find fundamental truths (supports diagnosis)
M|Rela|- **|Visual st diagnosis tool showing evolution and dependencies
